04094nmm a2200589Ia 9781501735967DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20182007nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017359677 a10.7591/97815017359672doi  a(DE-B1597)514743  a(OCoLC)1083618814  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY04a3372231 aLincoln, Edward J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWinners without Losers :bWhy Americans Should Care More about Global Economic Policy /cEdward J. Lincoln. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b13 tables, 42 charts/graphs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aA Council on Foreign Relations Book0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the two decades since the United States became the world's only superpower, policymakers in Washington have seemingly abandoned many tools of statecraft and instead now rely on U.S. military strength as the key—and sometimes the sole—element of its global strategy. Yet economists see a world in which the salience of military power has been shrinking as greater affluence and deepening interdependence transform the global economy.In Winners without Losers, Edward J. Lincoln, a highly regarded economist, contends that the best chance the United States has of ensuring peace and prosperity—for itself and for the rest of the world—will be found at conference tables rather than on the battlefield. Shining a spotlight on foreign trade policy as an agent for political change, this cogent and well-argued book urges policymakers, the business community, and citizens to find a path to increased stability by forging stronger international economic ties.Interdependence is founded on cooperation with other nations, and in particular on multilateral institutions. Over the past five years, in particular, American policy has moved strongly away from cooperation and, in a single-minded pursuit of the "war against global terror," has largely ignored economic issues. Extending the scope of his previous work, which started with the economic transformations of postwar Japan and more recently considered the evolution of economic linkages and cooperation in East Asia, Lincoln applies regional lessons to the world stage. More than a critique of current policies, Winners without Losers argues for a transformation of American foreign policy that recognizes the new realities of the globalized world-realities that America's leaders ignore at the nation's peril.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aEconomic historyy1945-. 0aEconomic policy. 0aGlobalizationxEconomic aspects. 0aInternational economic relations. 0aInternational relationsxEconomic aspects. 4aGeneral Economics. 4aPolitical Science & Political History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150173596740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501735967423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501735967/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles